1.Redux Toolkit store architecture:-
Redux Toolkit's architecture is built upon a well-structured foundation that simplifies state management while maintaining Redux's core principles. At its heart, 
the architecture revolves around three fundamental concepts: the store, slices, and reducers, all working together in a unidirectional data flow pattern.
The store configuration layer serves as the central hub of Redux Toolkit applications. The configureStore API provides a streamlined way to set up the Redux store with 
sensible defaults. This layer automatically configures middleware, enables Redux DevTools integration, and combines reducers.
example:-
import { configureStore } from '@reduxjs/toolkit'
import counterReducer from './counterSlice'
import userReducer from './userSlice'

const store = configureStore({
  reducer: {
    counter: counterReducer,
    user: userReducer
  },
  middleware: (getDefaultMiddleware) =>
    getDefaultMiddleware().concat(customMiddleware),
  devTools: process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production'
})


2.Slices & reducers:-
-A slice in Redux Toolkit is a self-contained piece of global state that includes:
A name (to identify the slice in the store)
An initial state
Reducers (functions that update the state)
Auto-generated actions (to trigger reducers)
Instead of manually creating action types, action creators, and reducers, Redux Toolkit does it all in one go!
A combination of state + reducers + actions in one place
example:
import { createSlice } from "@reduxjs/toolkit";

const counterSlice = createSlice({
  name: "counter",

  initialState: {
    value: 0,
  },

  reducers: {
    increment: (state) => {
      state.value += 1;
    },

    decrement: (state) => {
      state.value -= 1;
    },

    incrementByAmount: (state, action) => {
      state.value += action.payload;
    },
  },
});

export const { increment, decrement, incrementByAmount } =
  counterSlice.actions;

export default counterSlice.reducer;

-Reducers modify the state when an action is dispatched.
Redux Toolkit automatically generates action creators with the same names as the reducers.
We export the reducer so it can be added to the store.
A reducer is a function that:
Takes current state + action
Returns new updated state
example:
function counterReducer(state = 0, action) {
  if (action.type === "increment") {
    return state + 1;
  }
  return state;
}


3.Async thunks for API fetching:-
Redux-Thunk is a middleware for Redux that allows you to write action creators that return a function instead of an action object. This function receives 
the store's dispatch method and getState function as arguments, allowing it to dispatch multiple actions, perform asynchronous operations, and access the current 
state if needed before dispatching an action.
Async thunks are a pattern (most commonly used with Redux Toolkit) to handle asynchronous API calls in a clean and scalable way.
Instead of writing messy async logic inside components, you move it into a centralized place (Redux), making your app easier to manage and test.
Basic example:-
export const addUser = createAsyncThunk(
  "users/addUser",
  async (newUser) => {
    const response = await fetch("https://api.com/users", {
      method: "POST",
      body: JSON.stringify(newUser),
      headers: {
        "Content-Type": "application/json",
      },
    });
    return response.json();
  }
);

4.Zustand lightweight store intro:-
Zustand is a state management library used to manage your app's data in React and Next.js. It's fast and easy to use, allowing you to share information between 
components without a lot of extra code. In this article, we are going to explore the use of Zustand and why it is better than other libraries.
Minimal Boilerplate: Zustand requires very little setup, making it quick to integrate.
Hooks-Based API: It uses React hooks, making it intuitive and easy to use.
Scalable: Suitable for both small and large applications.
Performance-Optimized: Zustand minimizes unnecessary re-renders, ensuring efficient updates.
-Create a Store
import create from 'zustand';
// Create a store
const useStore = create((set) => ({
  count: 0,
  increment: () => set((state) => ({ count: state.count + 1 })),
  decrement: () => set((state) => ({ count: state.count - 1 })),
}));

-Bind the Component to the Store
function Counter() {
  // Bind the component to the store
  const { count, increment, decrement } = useStore();
  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={increment}>Increment</button>
      <button onClick={decrement}>Decrement</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default Counter;


5.React Query for server state:-
React Query is a data-fetching library for React that helps you manage server state — data that comes from an external source like an API. Unlike client state 
(which is local to your application and managed with tools like useState and useReducer), server state can be more difficult to handle because it needs to be 
fetched, cached, and kept in sync with the server.
React Query abstracts away much of this complexity by providing hooks and utilities that make it easier to work with server state. It automates many of the common 
tasks involved in data fetching, such as caching, background updates, and error handling.
//Wrap your app with QueryClientProvider:
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import App from "./App";

import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from "@tanstack/react-query";

const queryClient = new QueryClient();

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));

root.render(
  <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
    <App />
  </QueryClientProvider>
);

//Basic Fetch Example (GET API):
import { useQuery } from "@tanstack/react-query";

function Users() {
  const { data, isLoading, error } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ["users"],

    queryFn: async () => {
      const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users");
      if (!res.ok) {
        throw new Error("Failed to fetch");
      }
      return res.json();
    },
  });

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error.message}</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>User List</h2>
      {data.map((user) => (
        <p key={user.id}>{user.name}</p>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

export default Users;

//Use Component:
import Users from "./Users";

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Users />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;


